const faqs = [
 { q: 'Can you paint or drill into a hard hat to add branding?', a: 'No. ANSI Z89.1 — the standard for industrial head protection — prohibits modifications to the shell, including paint, drilling, heat application, or any decoration that alters the protective structure. Branding must be applied as a vinyl decal that adheres to the surface without chemical or mechanical alteration of the shell.' },
 { q: 'What kind of stickers are OSHA-compliant for hard hats?', a: 'Pressure-sensitive vinyl decals applied per the manufacturer\'s placement guidelines are compliant. The decal cannot cover or obscure the manufacturer\'s identification, ANSI rating mark, or date of manufacture. Most hard hat manufacturers (MSA, Pyramex, Bullard, 3M) publish placement diagrams for compliant decoration.' },
 { q: 'Where can a logo decal go on a hard hat?', a: 'Front, back, and side panels are typically allowed within manufacturer-defined zones. The crown is generally restricted because it\'s where impact distribution occurs. Each manufacturer publishes specific placement diagrams — check the spec sheet for the exact hat model before applying decals.' },
 { q: 'How do you brand hard hats for Local 433, Local 416, or other ironworker affiliations?', a: 'Vinyl-cut decals with the local number, journeyman/apprentice designation, and company logo. Most ironworking outfits apply company logo on the front, local affiliation on the back or sides. We supply the decals; the worker applies them per manufacturer placement rules.' },
 { q: 'Do hard hat decals expire or need to be replaced?', a: 'The decal itself doesn\'t have a regulatory expiration, but hard hats themselves typically have a 5-year service life from date of manufacture, or shorter if the shell is damaged. When a hard hat is retired and replaced, the decals are reapplied to the new shell.' },
]

